&= 4000 \text{ drips}
\end{align}
Get it, cake? If a drip of water is $\frac{1}{4}$ to the editor per milliliter then in a consider water that is $1539 \text{ milliliters}$, the number of drops we find are at our fingertips!<answer> Assuming a liter of water contains $4000$ drips, if each drip is $\frac{1}{4}$ of a milliliter, as given, we can determine the volume of water by multiplying the number of drips by the volume of one drip:
\begin{align}
\text{Volume of in a liter} &= 4000 \text{ drips} \times \frac{1}{4} \text{ milliliter per drip} \\
&= 1000 \text{ milliliters}
\end{align}
As $1000$ milliliters is equivalent to $1$ liter, the number of drips in a liter of water is indeed $4000$. Therefore, in $1539 \text{ milliliters}$ of water, the number of drips is:
